# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1929-chicago-cubs-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] The **1929 Chicago Cubs season** was the 58th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 54th in the National League and the 14th at Wrigley Field.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished first in the National League with a record of 98–54, 10.5 games ahead of the second place Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] The team was defeated four games to one by the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1929 World Series.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] Rogers Hornsby, who was acquired from the Boston Braves in an offseason deal, had a career year, hitting .380.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] In the process, he hit 39 home runs with 149 RBIs and led the league with a .679 slugging percentage.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] The 156 runs scored by Hornsby in 1929 were the most by a right-handed batter in the National League during the 20th century.
[src:1929-chicago-cubs-season/1929-chicago-cubs-season] Hornsby collected his second Most Valuable Player award that year, and for the second time he won a National League pennant.
